# Cloudflare Pages — HTTP headers
# https://developers.cloudflare.com/pages/configuration/headers/
#
# Cloudflare Pages ACCUMULATES headers from every matching rule. Putting
# Cache-Control in both a path-specific rule and the global /* rule
# produces a duplicate Cache-Control header value at request time, which
# defeats the long-cache directive for hashed assets. So:
#   - Global rule sets ONLY security headers.
#   - Specific rules set Cache-Control without overlap.
#   - HTML responses inherit Cloudflare Pages' default short cache.
#
# GitHub Pages ignores this file, so the parallel GH Pages deploy is
# unaffected during the migration.

# ── Security headers — apply to every response ──────────────────────────
# UAT 2026-05-13 P1-2: frame-ancestors must be delivered as a header (CSP3
# ignores it via <meta>). UAT P1-3: wss://*.supabase.co added to connect-src
# so Supabase Realtime websockets used by /ship are not blocked.
/*
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  Permissions-Policy: geolocation=(), microphone=(), camera=()
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; img-src 'self' https: data:; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline'; script-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' 'unsafe-eval'; font-src 'self' data:; connect-src 'self' https://*.supabase.co wss://*.supabase.co; media-src 'self' https://*.supabase.co; frame-ancestors 'none'; base-uri 'self'; form-action 'self'

# ── Hashed static assets — long-lived, immutable ────────────────────────
# Next.js writes /_next/static/* with content-hashed filenames; safe to
# cache effectively forever. This is the rule GH Pages can't match
# (its 600s cap costs ~4-8 Lighthouse Best Practices points).
/_next/static/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# Hashed font files served by next/font
/*.woff2
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable
